    grammar: { title: `Will vs Going to — Futur en anglais`, content: `Two main ways to express the future: 'Will' is for: spontaneous decisions ('I'll help you' — J'vais t'aider), predictions without evidence ('It will be sunny tomorrow'), promises ('I will call you'). 'Going to' is for: planned intentions ('I'm going to visit Paris next month' — J'ai prévu de visiter Paris), predictions based on evidence ('Look at those clouds — it's going to rain'). Quick rule: if you've already planned it → going to. If you decide right now → will. Both are correct in many situations, so don't overthink it!` },
