    grammar: { title: `Gradable vs Non-gradable adjectives`, content: `In English, adjectives work differently with intensifiers. 'Gradable' adjectives (big, cold, tired) can be modified: very big, quite cold, a bit tired. 'Non-gradable' or 'extreme' adjectives (huge, freezing, exhausted) already contain the idea of maximum degree — you don't say 'very freezing'. Instead use: absolutely, completely, utterly, totally. 'Absolutely freezing', 'completely exhausted', 'totally amazing'. Common extreme adjectives: tiny (= very small), starving (= very hungry), furious (= very angry), gorgeous (= very beautiful), hilarious (= very funny). Using the right intensifier makes your English sound very natural.` },
